🧪 Lab 03 - User Role Controlled by Request Parameter
Platform: PortSwigger Web Security Academy
Category: Access Control
Difficulty: Apprentice
Status: ✅ Solved

Objective
Identify and exploit an application that controls user privileges using a client-side request parameter.

Background
The application stores the user's administrative status inside a cookie. Since cookies are fully controlled by the client, modifying this value may allow privilege escalation.

Methodology
Logged into the application as a normal user.
Intercepted requests using Burp Suite.
Observed the following cookie in multiple requests:
Admin=false
Sent the request to Burp Repeater.
Modified the cookie:
Admin=true
Requested the administrator interface:
GET /admin
Successfully accessed the administrator panel.
Located the delete endpoint for the user carlos.
Sent the following request:
GET /admin/delete?username=carlos
Received a 302 Found redirect to /admin.
Verified that the lab was solved.
Vulnerability
Broken Access Control
The server trusted a client-controlled cookie to determine administrative privileges.

Evidence
Original cookie:

Admin=false
Modified cookie:

Admin=true
Administrative action performed:

Deleted user: carlos
Impact
An attacker can modify the cookie to gain administrator privileges, resulting in:

Unauthorized access to administrative interfaces
User deletion
Data modification
Full application compromise
Severity: Critical

Root Cause
Authorization decisions were based on client-supplied data instead of server-side session validation.

Remediation
Developers should:

Store user roles on the server.
Associate roles with authenticated sessions.
Ignore client-supplied privilege values.
Perform authorization checks for every privileged request.
Burp Suite Skills Practiced
Proxy
HTTP History
Repeater
Cookie Manipulation
Manual Request Editing
Response Analysis
Pentester's Notes
The application exposed an Admin cookie that directly controlled authorization.

By modifying the cookie from false to true, administrator access was obtained without exploiting authentication.

This demonstrates why authorization must never rely on client-controlled data.

Lessons Learned
Never trust client-side cookies for authorization.
Cookies are easily modified using Burp Suite.
Authorization must always be enforced on the server.
Successful exploitation often requires both modifying the request and targeting the appropriate endpoint.
